"/>  If you consider how wheat is harvested, this use is not
realistic. Sheaves were made and stacked in the field, and not
trimmed up later.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I was also told it was used to make broom heads.

"/>  More likely ... can make broom and then whack the straggling
strands off.
It could also have been used for chopping feed, like turnips,
potatos, corn ears, or even hay, for feeding young animals.

the best source for identifying these things is an OLD Sears
Catalog. Look in your library for a reproduction and check the
farm utensildin the front.
